                <h2>Conclusion First: Creative Pool Depth Determines Cold Launch Success</h2>
<p>In the TikTok Shop new product cold launch stage, while account structure and bidding strategies matter, what truly determines success or failure is <strong>the depth and quality of your creative pool</strong>. A creative pool isn't simply uploading a few videos to an ad group—it's a systematically planned reserve of multiple creative variations. Insufficient or homogeneous creative pools cause the ad system to fail at effectively learning audience characteristics, making it difficult to break through cold launch bottlenecks even with higher bids.</p>
<p>When a utility app operations team cold launched in the Southeast Asian market, they prepared only 5 creative pieces in the first week, with highly similar video styles. The ad system took two weeks to complete model learning, and their CPA (cost per acquisition) reached 2.3x the expected target. After expanding to 20 differentiated creatives, system learning efficiency improved significantly, and CPA returned to target levels by the third week.</p>
<h2>Step 1: Define Testing Matrix, Avoid Ineffective Volume</h2>
<p>The biggest mistake during cold launch is "one video to rule them all" or "let's just shoot 5 and try." The first step in building a creative pool is <strong>establishing a clear testing matrix</strong>.</p>
<p>The testing matrix should cover three dimensions:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Content formats</strong>: Horizontal talking head, vertical situational drama, product feature showcase, UGC-style recommendations</li>
<li><strong>Core selling points</strong>: Each selling point needs 2-3 supporting creatives, avoiding repeated testing of a single point</li>
<li><strong>Duration combinations</strong>: 6-15 second fast-paced creatives alongside 30-60 second in-depth recommendation content</li>
</ul>
<p>Taking a cross-border e-commerce team launching in the UK market as an example, they prepared 12 creatives for a home product, divided into three test groups: Group 1 focused on product usage scenarios, Group 2 emphasized cost-performance comparison, and Group 3 featured local KOC (Key Opinion Consumer) authentic presence. Final data showed the KOC group had 40% higher CTR (click-through rate) than other groups, becoming the main volume-driving creative.</p>
<h2>Step 2: Control Creative Launch Rhythm, Prevent Account Weight Dilution</h2>
<p>Building a creative pool isn't about throwing all creatives in at once. Operational experience shows that <strong>launching more than 3 creatives simultaneously in the same ad group significantly extends system learning time</strong>, potentially causing model confusion and inability to identify which creative truly performs.</p>
<p>A tiered scaling strategy is recommended:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Days 1-3</strong>: Only 2 core creatives per ad group, observe CTR and conversion cost</li>
<li><strong>Days 4-7</strong>: Based on performance, shut down underperformers and add 2-3 new variants</li>
<li><strong>After Day 8</strong>: Keep volume drivers, open new ad groups to test new creative directions</li>
</ol>
<p>A beauty brand made a common mistake during TikTok Shop cold launch—testing 15 creatives simultaneously in the first week, causing overall ad group CPA to remain high. After adjusting strategy to batch creatives with no more than 5 per batch, CPA decreased 35% week-over-week in the second week.</p>
<h2>Step 3: Establish Creative Elimination Mechanism, Maintain Pool Activity</h2>
<p>A creative pool isn't a one-time project but a dynamic system requiring continuous updates. <strong>After the cold launch period, retain at least 20% of the best-performing creatives as baseline</strong>, while maintaining a <strong>30% ratio of new creative testing</strong>.</p>
<p>Elimination criteria recommendations:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Metric</th>
<th>Elimination Threshold</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>CTR (Click-through Rate)</td>
<td>Below category average by 50%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Conversion Rate</td>
<td>Below ad group average by 30%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>CPA (Cost Per Acquisition)</td>
<td>Exceeding target by 2x for 3 consecutive days</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>A fashion seller conducts weekly creative reviews, eliminating creatives with CTR below 1% and supplementing with new product shoots. Within three months, their creative pool expanded from initial 18 to 85 pieces, with 15 continuously contributing over 80% of GMV.</p>
<h2>Cold Launch Pitfall Reminders from an Operator's Perspective</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Don't just look at CTR</strong>: High click rate but low conversion may indicate clickbait attracting non-target audiences</li>
<li><strong>Localization isn't translation</strong>: The same product needs reshooting or deep localization adaptation for different markets</li>
<li><strong>Avoid copyright risks</strong>: Popular BGMs and internet memes need confirmed licensing to prevent creative takedowns</li>
<li><strong>Budget allocation must be generous</strong>: During cold launch, daily budget per creative should be no less than $20 to ensure sufficient data for system learning</li>
</ol>
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>The essence of TikTok Shop new product cold launch is <strong>creative efficiency competition</strong>. A healthy creative pool should contain diverse content formats, clear batch testing rhythms, and clear elimination and refresh mechanisms. Rather than believing in black-hat bidding tactics or mysterious optimization, invest energy in upstream creative planning and filming—your creative pool determines your cold launch ceiling, not the budget sitting in your account.</p>
